etymologies: late Middle English; earliest use found in Cursor Mundi: a Northumbrian poem of the 14th century. Probably originally from runkle + -ed; in later use also partly from runkle + -ed

definitions: Wrinkled, rumpled; (in later use also, of fabric, clothing, etc.) rucked up.

notes.text: Apparently largely restricted to Scottish use between the 16th and early 20th centuries.
